\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\f2 When you click on an icon, it becomes focused (with a dotted box around it).  It is also selected if it has a grey background.  Some file operations work on all selected items, others just on the focused one.}{\f2 

\par }{\f2 
\par }{\b\f2 To select a single item}{\b\f2 
\par }{\f2 
\par }{\f2 Click on the icon with the left mouse button.  }{\f2 
\par }{\f2 
\par }{\b\f2 To select a range}{\b\f2 
\par }{\f2 
\par }{\f2 1   Select the first item in the range.}{\f2 
\par }{\f2 2   Hold down SHIFT.}{\f2 
\par }{\f2 3   Select the last item in the range. }{\f2 
\par }{\f2 
\par }{\b\f2 To toggle the selection of a single item}{\b\f2 
\par }{\f2 
\par }{\f2 Hold down CTRL when you left-click on it.}{\f2 
\par }{\f2 
\par }{\b\f2 To select a block}{\b\f2 
\par }{\f2 
\par }{\f2 Press the left mouse button when the cursor is to the top left of an icon.  Then stretch the lasso around the icons you wish to select.}{\f2 
\par }{\f2 
\par }{\b\f2 To de-select items}{\b\f2 
\par }{\f2 
\par }{\f2 Click on an unselected file/folder or click on an empty space.  }{\f2 
\par }{\f2 
\par }{\b\f2 To select or de-select everything in the window}{\b\f2 
\par }{\f2 
\par }\pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 Left click on the right hand label.  If there are items currently highlighted, all items are de-selected.  Otherwise everything is selected.
\par 
\par {\b To select files using wildcards}{\b 
\par }
\par Right click on the right hand label to open the Select Files box.
\par \pard \s5\fi-720\li720 
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} Explorer}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $} Explorer}} 
{\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} explorer; tree; selecting folders}} Explorer
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par This displays all drives and folders in a branching structure similar to File Manager.  Use it to give a broad view of your file system while you navigate through the folders.
\par 
\par \{bml explorer.bmp\}
\par 
\par {\b Win95 Explorer style view}{\b 
\par }
\par To combine the tree with an icon window for an interface like the Windows 95 Explorer, right click on the tree and check the "Show file window" menu item.  Now when you click on a node of the tree, the icon window is updated to display the contents of tha
t folder.
\par 
\par {\b Selecting folders}{\b 
\par }
\par When you are using a dialog box and are asked to choose a folder, you can double click on the edit box to open a tree view.  Move through the tree as usual, and when you have found the right folder, press Enter or choose Op
en Folder from the popup menu.  To cancel the operation, close the window or press Escape.
\par 
\par {\b See also:}{\b \line }{\uldb Icon windows}{\v IconWindows}
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} Bin}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $} Wastepaper Bin}} 
{\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} bin; trash; emptying the bin; restoring files}} Wastepaper Bin
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par When you drop files or folders into the bin icon, they are moved to hidden directories instead of being deleted.  If you change your mind, you can restore them to their original location.  Otherwise, you'll need to empty the bin to free up the space used 
by the files.
\par 
\par Double click on the icon to open the bin window.
\par 
\par \{bml bin.bmp\}
\par 
\par {\b How to restore files}{\b 
\par }
\par After selecting the items, choose Restore from the popup menu to move each file or folder back to where it came from.  Alternatively, drag the items to an icon window or shortcut.  This moves them all to that location.
\par 
\par {\b How to empty the bin}{\b 
\par }
\par The popup menu has Delete and Empty commands, which deletes selected items and all trash, respectively.  If you choose Properties from the menu, you can configure the bin to clear trash automatically.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} Taskbar}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $} Taskbar}} 
{\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} taskbar}} Taskbar
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par Each running process has a button on the bar and you click on a button to switch to that task.  If you right click instead, a popup menu lets you minimize, maximize or close the window.
\par 
\par \{bml taskbar.bmp\}
\par 
\par The start button has a special popup menu that lets you setup the taskbar.  Choose {\uldb Taskbar Properties}{\v TaskbarProp} from this menu to adjust the settings.  
\par 
\par You can configure the taskbar to always stay on screen or hide when the cursor moves off it.  It will always pop up when the cursor reaches the bottom of the screen.
\par 
\par {\b See also:}{\b 
\par }{\uldb Start menu}{\v StartMenu}
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} StartMenu}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $} Start menu}}
 {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} start menu; menu}} Start menu
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par This nested menu is displayed when you press Start on the taskbar. Each menu item is equivalent to a program item in Program Manager.  Additionally, it can open new windows and dialogs, and programs that are launched from the Start menu will be shown by y
our chosen icon on the taskbar, even Windows programs.
\par 
\par \{bml start.bmp\}
\par 
\par To edit the start menu, right click on the Start button and choose {\uldb Start Properties}{\v StartMenuProp} from the popup menu.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} References}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Shortcuts and aliases}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} shortcuts; aliases}} Shortcuts and aliases
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par Shortcuts and aliases are references -- they point to another object such as a disk drive, folder or file.  When you open or drop things into a reference, the effect is the same as if you had opened or dropped into the original object.
\par 
\par {\b Shortcuts}{\b 
\par }
\par These are icons on the desktop, and you create them by dragging an icon out of a window and releasing the mouse.  The shortcut is saved in Calmira's INI file when you quit.  To edit its properties, click on its caption and choose {\uldb Properties}{\v 
ReferenceProp} from the menu.
\par 
\par Shortcuts are useful when used sparingly -- you would probably have shortcuts of your disk drives and a few important folders and utilities on your desktop.
\par 
\par {\b Aliases}{\b 
\par }
\par These are small files (with an extension ALS) containing an icon and some data that points to the original object. To create an alias, select an object, right click over it and choose Create Alias from the menu.  The alias is added to the window's content
s.
\par 
\par Aliases are just like other files, and you can copy, move or delete them without affecting the original object.  To change their properties, right click and select the Edit Alias command.
\par 
\par You can use aliases to give the effect of a free floating program group: move aliases into the one folder, create a shortcut of the folder, and change its icon.  They are also useful for creating "virtual links" to other folders, to change the apparent st
ructure of your directory tree.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} FileManagement}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $} File Ma
nagement}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} file management; files; copying; moving; deleting; renaming; refreshing windows}} File Management
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par {\b Copying}{\b 
\par }
\par 1.  Ensure the destination is visible, as a window or an icon.
\par 2.  Select which objects to copy.
\par 3.  Drag them to the destination and release the mouse.
\par 
\par {\b Moving}{\b 
\par }
\par 1.  Ensure the destination is visible, as a window or an icon.
