\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par Shortcuts, aliases and start menu items can use MS-DOS environment variables in their settings.  The {\i Target}, {\i Parameters}, {\i Command}, {\i Icon file} and {\i Working Folder}
 fields (where applicable) can contain environment variable names (surrounded by %) like lines in MS-DOS batch files.  When you activate an item, the variable values are substituted for the names.
\par 
\par {\b Special environment strings}{\b 
\par }
\par {\b %currentfolder%} points to the directory showing in the active icon window (if none are active, the variable is empty).  This is particularly useful for the {\i Working Folder}
 field when you want to create or modify files in the current folder.  For instance, if you use it for a Notepa
d shortcut, Notepad will always start up in the directory you are viewing, so you can open and save/create files without having to hunt through the tree.
\par 
\par {\b %droppedfiles%} is only valid immediately after files have been dropped into a file shortcut or alias.  It contains the list of filenames, and you can place it in the {\i Parameters}
 field to insert the filenames between other parameters.  If %droppedfiles% is omitted, the files are just appended to the parameters list.
\par 
\par {\b %calmira%} points to the program's home directory.
\par 
\par {\b %comspec%} is defined automatically by MS-DOS, and gives the filename of the command interpreter (i.e. the MS-DOS shell), which is usually command.com.
\par 
\par {\b %windir%} is defined automatically by Windows and points to the Windows directory.
\par 
\par 
\par {\b User defined variables}{\b 
\par }
\par The {\b [Environment]} section of the INI file is added to Calmira's own environment after loading, so it has the same effect as the MS-DOS {\b set} command.  As with MS-DOS, don't add the % characters when making settings -- they are onl
y used when variables are referred to.  
\par 
\par Use this section to store your own identifiers, such as folder locations and device names.  When a folder or device changes, just edit the environment and all shortcuts, aliases and menu items will refer to the right place automatically.
\par 
\par 
\par {\b Note}: the icon {\i index} is not affected by the environment, so you should use something like %filename%(1) when re-mapping the icon file.
