 Find Files dialog}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} find; searching; files; folders}} Find Files dialog
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par \{bml find.bmp\}
\par 
\par This dialog lets you search for files on the whole or part of a drive.  You can open it from the start menu, desktop popup menu, system window or icon windows.
\par 
\par To look for multiple sets of files, separate each specification with a semi-colon.  When you press the Search button, the search takes place in the background and you can carry on with other tasks.  Files and folders are displayed in the listbox as soon a
s they are found.
\par 
\par Double click on an item to open it, or right click on the listbox to display commands that let you open an item's parent folder or delete it.  Ctrl and Shift can be used to select multiple items, and they can be dropped into other programs.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} RunProgram}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Run Program dialog}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} run; launch; programs}} Run Program dialog
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par \{bml run.bmp\}
\par 
\par This dialog lets you start a Windows or MS-DOS program, or execute an MS-DOS command.  You can open it from the start menu, desktop menu, system window or icon windows.
\par 
\par If you check the {\b DOS command }check box, the text you type in is passed to your command interpreter so you can obtain directory listings etc..  Otherwise, the text is passed to Windows to execute.
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} StartMenuProp}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Start Menu properties dialog}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} start menu; menus; bitmaps}} Start Menu properties dialog
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par \{bml strtprop.bmp\}
\par 
\par Open this dialog by right clicking on the Start button of the taskbar, and choose Start Properties.  This dialog is not modal, so you can switch windows and drop items into the tree.
\par 
\par {\b Creating new items}{\b 
\par }
\par There are three ways of doing this:
\par 
\par 1.  Press the Add or Insert buttons on the toolbar.
\par 2.  Drag and drop files and folders from icon windows straight into the tree.
\par 3.  Press the Import Groups button to copy items from Program Manager.
\par 
\par {\b Creating new sub-menus}{\b 
\par }
\par A sub-menu starts off as a normal menu item.  When you use the Insert button or drag nodes onto it, it becomes a menu.  When the contents are deleted, it becomes an item again.
\par 
\par {\b Copying and moving items and sub-menus}{\b 
\par }
\par Simply drag a node to move it.  To drop a node into a closed sub-menu, hold down ALT before releasing the mouse button.  To copy a single item, hold down the CTRL key when dropping.
\par 
\par {\b Built-in menu commands}{\b 
\par }
\par Instead of specifying a program to run, the {\b command line}
 field of a menu item can open or activate a window in Calmira.  The recognised commands are in the drop-down list.  The $Folder command opens an icon window, and requires a directory name as parameter.  If wildcard characters * or ? are present
 in the parameter, they are used as the filter.  For example, {\b $Folder c:}{\b \\}{\b windows}{\b \\}{\b *.exe} displays all the executables, whereas {\b $Folder c:}{\b \\}{\b windows} displays everything.
\par 
\par {\b Using bitmap files in the start menu}{\b 
\par }
\par To use a Window bitmap (bmp) file for a menu item instead of an icon, type in the full name of the bitmap file in the {\b Icon from} edit box. This bitmap should be 16 x 16 pixels, but can have any number of colours.
\par 
\par {\b Adding menu separators}{\b 
\par }
\par A dash "-" as the first character of a caption will turn the entry into a separator line.  Each item must have a different caption, so use something like -1, -2 ... for multiple separators.
\par 
\par 
\par See also:
\par {\uldb Environment variables}{\v Environment}
\par 
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} SystemProp}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $}
 System Properties dialog}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} system}} System Properties dialog
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par \{bml sysprop.bmp\}
\par 
\par This dialog contains global, screen display and network settings.  
\par 
\par {\b Advanced settings}{\b 
\par }
\par The Advanced page contains an INI file edi
tor that lets you modify Calmira's configuration file without using a separate text editor.  Double click on a section name to show the settings it contains.  The identifiers (on the left) are not case sensitive, but the values (on the right) {\i are}
.  The order in which lines appear does not usually matter.
\par 
\par Many of the INI file settings can be adjusted through various dialog boxes, and these should be left alone.  You should also leave settings that are updated automatically, such as window positions.
\par 
\par {\b Note}: Some settings will not take effect until you restart the program.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} ReferenceProp}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Shortcut and Alias Properties dialog}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} shortcuts; aliases}} Shortcut and Alias Properties dialog
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par \{bml refprop.bmp\}
\par 
\par To edit a shortcut, click once on its caption and choose Properties.  To edit an alias, right click on it and choose the Edit Alias command.
\par 
\par {\b\i Parameters}{\b  field}{\b 
\par }
\par As well as typing in parameters, you can specify where in the command line to insert the names of files which are dropped into the shortcut or alias.  Place the string %droppedfiles% at the desired location, and when you drop any files, it will be replace
d with filenames.  
\par 
\par {\b\i Use document folder}{\b  setting}{\b 
\par }
\par This controls how dropped files are passed to programs via the command line.  
\par 
\par When the box is checked, only the filenames are passed, and the location of the first file is temporarily used as the wor
king folder.  Since the length of the command line is limited, this feature allows more files to be dropped, but might not work with all programs.
\par 
\par When the box is unchecked, the full pathnames are passed.
\par 
\par See also:
\par {\uldb Environment variables}{\v Environment}
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} TaskbarProp}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Taskbar Properties dialog}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} taskbar}} Taskbar Properties dialog
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par \{bml taskprop.bmp\}
\par 
\par Open this dialog by right clicking on the Start button and choosing Taskbar Properties.
\par 
\par {\b Excluding programs from the bar}{\b 
\par }
\par If certain programs are finding their way onto the taskbar that you would rather exclude, add the program's filename (without the path) to the exclusion list.  Optionally, leave a space after the name and enter a window classname, to exclude only a partic
ular kind of window.  
\par 
\par You can find class names by selecting {\b Spy} from the Start button's menu, and watching the button hints, which will now tell you the filename and classname of each task button.
\par 
\par {\b Refresh interval setting}{\b 
\par }
\par This determines how often the taskbar updates the button captions and removes any buttons for windows that have disappeared from the screen without being detected in the normal way.
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} SystemTray}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $} System tray
}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} system tray}} System tray
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par The taskbar's clock can hold a few icons for commonly used utilities.  These programs are treated slightly differently from those launched by normal shortcuts:
\par 
\par They are not allocated a button on the taskbar, and when you minimize the program, it's icon is always hidden.  When you try to run the program from the system tray again, an existing instance is restored if possible, rather than always launching another 
instance.
\par 
\par Edit the {\b [System tray]} section to include a list of programs, which can be ordinary Windows programs.  The following example demonstrates the effect of adding a volume control and calculator:
\par 
\par \pard\plain \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\f5 [System Tray]}{\f5 
\par }{\f5 Count=2}{\f5 
\par }{\f5 S0=c:}{\f5 \\}{\f5 sbpro}{\f5 \\}{\f5 winappl}{\f5 \\}{\f5 sbpmi}{\f5 xer.exe}{\f5 
\par }\pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 {\f5 S1=c:}{\f5 \\}{\f5 windows}{\f5 \\}{\f5 calc.exe}{\f5 
\par }
\par This yields \{bmc systray.bmp\}.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn \b\f2\cf2\lang2057 \page {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 #} CustomDriveNames}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Custom drive names}} {\plain \f3\fs16\up6\lang2057 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245 \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\fs16\up6 K} drives; disk drives}} Custom drive names
\par \pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 
\par Calmira does not distinguish between different types of floppy or removable drives.  You can override the default names given to disk drives by adding suitable descriptions to the [Drives] section of the INI file.
\par 
\par Assign a description to each drive letter that you want to describe manually, for example
\par 
\par \pard\plain \f3\fs20\lang2057 {\f5 [Drives]}{\f5 
\par }{\f5 A=3}{\f5 \'bd}{\f5 " Floppy}{\f5 
\par }{\f5 B=5}{\f5 \'bc}{\f5 " Floppy}{\f5 
\par }\pard\plain \s5 \f2\fs20\lang2057 {\f5 E=Syquest}{\f5 
\par }
